proliferation of fetal images in various media, such as medical journals, magazines, and motion pictures, few have openly addressed the problems that the emergence of the fetal subject poses for feminism. Fetal Subjects, Feminist Positions foregrounds feminism's effort to focus on the importance of women's reproductive agency, and at the same time acknowledges the increasing significance of fetal subjects in public discourse and private experience. Essays address the public fascination with the fetal subject and its implications for abortion discourse and feminist commitment to reproductive rights in the United States. Contributors include scholars from fields as diverse as anthropology, communications, political science, sociology, and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAbortionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFeminist theory. 0aFetusxImaging. 0aHuman reproductionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aWomen's rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aMichaels, Meredith Wilson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorgan, Lynn M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z97831104425260 cprintz978081223496140uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280756140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512807561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781512807561.jpg  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK